<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="023" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Implement Claude Code TaskCompleted Quality Gate Hook</title>
    <phase>3: Automation Pipelines</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>2</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>022</dependencies>
    <blocks>043</blocks>
    <tags>automation, hooks, claude-code, quality-gate</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Create a Claude Code TaskCompleted hook script at scripts/quality/task-quality-gate.sh. On task
    completion the hook runs three checks: (1) dotnet build -warnaserror to verify the build is clean,
    (2) lint all files changed in the current git diff, (3) run architecture tests if any .cs files
    are in the diff. Register the hook in .claude/settings.json. The hook must not block on warnings
    for non-code tasks and must only run architecture tests if .cs files are present in the diff.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    DevOps engineer specializing in Claude Code hooks and quality gate automation. Expert in git diff
    analysis, shell scripting, and integrating architecture tests into automated workflows.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A TaskCompleted hook that enforces a lightweight quality gate at the end of every Claude Code task
    execution. The gate catches build breaks, lint violations in changed files, and architecture test
    failures before a task is considered complete — without adding significant latency for documentation
    or non-code tasks.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      The TaskCompleted hook fires when Claude Code finishes a task (after the task-execute skill
      marks it complete). This is the last checkpoint before the user sees the task completion
      message. The hook has access to the full repository context and can run commands.

      Gate design:
      - Build check: `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ -warnaserror` — treats warnings as
        errors. If this fails, the hook reports the failure clearly so Claude Code can see it.
      - Changed files lint: Use `git diff --name-only HEAD` to get changed files. For each .cs file
        run dotnet format --verify-no-changes. For each .ts/.tsx file run eslint.
      - Architecture tests: If any .cs files appear in `git diff --name-only HEAD`, run
        `dotnet test tests/Spaarke.ArchTests/ --no-build` (skip build since gate step 1 already built).
        Skip architecture tests entirely if no .cs files changed.

      Non-code task detection: If `git diff --name-only HEAD` returns only .md, .json config, .yaml,
      or .poml files (no .cs, .ts, .tsx, .ps1), skip the build and architecture tests — run only
      the file-type-appropriate linters for changed files.

      The hook must complete in under 2 minutes total. Architecture tests (6 classes) typically run
      in ~30 seconds so this is feasible.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>scripts/quality/task-quality-gate.sh (create)</file>
      <file>.claude/settings.json (modify — register hook)</file>
      <file>scripts/quality/post-edit-lint.sh (read — reuse linting logic via sourcing or calling)</file>
      <file>tests/Spaarke.ArchTests/ (read — understand test structure for correct test command)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="spec">Hook MUST NOT block or add significant latency for documentation-only tasks (tasks where git diff contains only .md, .poml, .yaml, .json files). Detect non-code tasks and skip build/arch tests.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Architecture tests MUST only run if .cs files appear in the git diff. Running arch tests for TypeScript-only changes is unnecessary overhead.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Hook output must be clearly structured so Claude Code can read the quality gate results and act on failures. Use a consistent format: [GATE: PASS/FAIL] prefix for each check.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">If the build fails (-warnaserror), the hook must exit non-zero to signal Claude Code that the task has unresolved issues.</constraint>
    <constraint source=".claude/settings.json">Must read existing .claude/settings.json before modifying. Preserve all existing keys, values, and previously registered hooks from task 022.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/spec.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read .claude/settings.json to understand the current structure including the PostToolUse hook registered in task 022. Plan the TaskCompleted hook addition without disturbing existing hooks.</step>
    <step order="2">Read tests/Spaarke.ArchTests/ structure to understand the project name and correct dotnet test command needed to run architecture tests in isolation.</step>
    <step order="3">Create scripts/quality/task-quality-gate.sh with bash shebang and executable permissions. Add global error trap consistent with post-edit-lint.sh.</step>
    <step order="4">Implement changed-files detection: run `git diff --name-only HEAD` and categorize results into arrays: CS_FILES (*.cs), TS_FILES (*.ts *.tsx), PS_FILES (*.ps1), DOC_FILES (*.md *.poml *.yaml *.json). Detect if this is a code change or documentation-only task.</step>
    <step order="5">Implement the non-code fast path: if no CS_FILES or TS_FILES, run only documentation-appropriate checks (e.g., verify .json files are valid JSON with python3 -m json.tool), print [GATE: SKIP — no code changes], and exit 0.</step>
    <step order="6">Implement gate step 1 (build check): run `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ -warnaserror --no-incremental 2>&1`. Print [GATE: PASS — build clean] or [GATE: FAIL — build errors]. Exit 1 if build fails.</step>
    <step order="7">Implement gate step 2 (lint changed files): iterate over CS_FILES and run dotnet format --verify-no-changes --include for each. Iterate over TS_FILES and run npx eslint for each. Accumulate and report results with [GATE: PASS/WARN — lint].</step>
    <step order="8">Implement gate step 3 (architecture tests): if CS_FILES is non-empty, run `dotnet test tests/Spaarke.ArchTests/ --no-build 2>&1`. Print [GATE: PASS — arch tests] or [GATE: FAIL — arch tests]. Exit 1 if tests fail.</step>
    <step order="9">Implement the summary section: print a consolidated gate report at the end: total checks run, pass/fail counts, and a final [QUALITY GATE: PASSED] or [QUALITY GATE: FAILED] line.</step>
    <step order="10">Update .claude/settings.json: add the TaskCompleted hook entry alongside the existing PostToolUse hook. Ensure the JSON structure is valid after modification.</step>
    <step order="11">Verify both scripts are executable and .claude/settings.json is valid JSON: `python3 -m json.tool .claude/settings.json`.</step>
    <step order="12">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 023 status from pending to completed.</step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="file">scripts/quality/task-quality-gate.sh</output>
    <output type="file">.claude/settings.json (updated with TaskCompleted hook registration)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>scripts/quality/task-quality-gate.sh exists and is executable</criterion>
    <criterion>Script correctly identifies code changes vs. documentation-only tasks via git diff --name-only</criterion>
    <criterion>Documentation-only tasks skip build and architecture tests (fast path)</criterion>
    <criterion>Architecture tests run only when .cs files appear in the git diff</criterion>
    <criterion>Build check uses -warnaserror flag and exits non-zero on failure</criterion>
    <criterion>Each gate step outputs a [GATE: PASS/FAIL] prefixed result line</criterion>
    <criterion>Summary section prints consolidated [QUALITY GATE: PASSED/FAILED] at end</criterion>
    <criterion>.claude/settings.json contains TaskCompleted hook registration</criterion>
    <criterion>PostToolUse hook from task 022 is preserved in .claude/settings.json (not overwritten)</criterion>
    <criterion>.claude/settings.json is valid JSON after modification</criterion>
    <criterion>TASK-INDEX.md updated to reflect task completion</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
